\begin{enumerate}
\item Plant phenology is changing with climate change:
\begin{enumerate}
\item Timing of spring bb is changing with anthropogenic climate change 
\item But changes are not uniform with some regions experiencing greater warming than others.
\item Responses are also  species specific and highly variable
\item Budburst in forest communities is the product of species differences as well as geographic variability in environmental cues.
\item Understanding the relative importance of these different drivers of budburst is needed to understand and predict future changes in spring phenology---and their ultimate impacts on growing season length, carbon cycle, species interactions
\end{enumerate}

\item Cues that shape bb
\begin{enumerate}
\item For woody plants, we do know there are three important environmental cues for bb:
\begin{enumerate}
\item Forcing: spring temperatures
\item Photoperiod/daylength
\item Chilling: winter length and temperatures
\end{enumerate}
\item But these cues interact---forcing can offset low chilling---photoperiod offsets weak forcing (Heide1993, Chuine2000, Caffarra2011, Flynn2018 )
\item The consistency and strength of these interactions across populations remains unclear.
\end{enumerate}

%DLAug28 --- edited the below to make it less broad
\item Cues can vary geographically and temporally---likely to create differences in community dynamics and species composition.
\begin{enumerate}
\item Increasing winter and spring temperatures = faster accumulation of chilling and forcing (Guy2014)---associated with earlier budburst in many temperate plant species.
\item Could create novel niche space early in growing season---facilitating spp invasions or novel community assemblages
\item Will also reduce fitness in spp with strong photoperiod cues = limited in their ability to advance  (Korner2010) = different competitive landscape later in the growing season
\item Differences in species cue responses are likely to shape the diversity and persistence of species across forest communities.
\end{enumerate}
