\item Variation in bb phenology across species in a community
\begin{enumerate}
\item To date, most work has been devoted to understanding how environmental cues shape phenology and what drives the high species level variation in budburst
\item Timing of bb in a forest community can span several weeks---species fill different temporal niche
\item e.g. understory spp tend to bb earlier than canopy species, likely reflecting overarching differences in traits.
\item But differences in budburst responses are likely to also exist across a species ranges.
\end{enumerate}

\item Across a species spatial distribution---differences in cues and therefore in spp responses/bb
\begin{enumerate}
 \item Species with large latitudinal distributions experience differences in cues---e.g. photoperiod cues 
 % \item May also be experiencing different rates of temperature change over time---e.g. diff rates climate change across North America (Kunkel2004) %DLAug28: I could see this fitting in the discussion---cues are changing at diff rates---diff rates of change in forest communities btwn east and west
 \item Budburst across diff pop = result of local selective pressures---abiotic (local envirt) and biotic (competition and herbivory) %DLAug21: is introducing biotic factors too much here? Save it for trait paper?
\item But few studies have explored how cue use may differ across spatial gradient for the same forest communities and the role of local environments and biotic communities in shaping budburst across North America. 
\end{enumerate}


% 
% \item Important to consider not just spp but communities as a whole---understand role phenology in shaping spp assemblages, community dynamics, and ecoystem services (Cleland2007).

\item In this study we:
\begin{enumerate}
\item Combined results from two growth chamber studies of woody plant phenological cues
\item Data from four populations, from eastern to western North America and a range of 4-6$^{\circ}$ latitude
\item Allows us to detect general trends in how bb of N Am. deciduous forest communities respond to forcing, chilling, photoperiod 
\item But also community specific responses---detect differences between Western and Eastern forest communities, and at different latitudes
\item And trends across different functional groups, exploring differences between shrub and tree species.
